fOZ_gddXs-SGXoqqH4ClcwE3h9EbYAPIsPJuhf0vJemQzisLbV35csdg3v7GTnfkquELl5l1tfcRQ37QZv4Y7mHE2R-f_3LaNWgNGe2BRvd\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring metadata implications**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering how empty committed reachability metadata might mean that nativeTestCompile can use generated metadata from a JVM run, which might eliminate our need to run it ourselves. The Gradle plugin could be running an agent during javaTest, creating metadata that the native compilation uses. Existing benchmark tests often rely on dynamic reflection on app classes despite lacking committed metadata, but perhaps that's fine since the native image includes test code's reflection metadata. \\\\n\\\\nHmm, I wonder if we can avoid needing Native reflection metadata by using a built-in Java annotation like `@Deprecated`.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering test design**\\\\n\\\\nI need to think about not hardcoding the version in my test class, which is `AnnotationCreatorTest.java`. Should I remove the placeholder? Leaving it might lead to a poorly structured test, but it'll be better if I replace the placeholder with something useful. However, since it's an active class with a one-to-one mapping, maybe a dedicated structure would be the way to go. I'll figure out the best approach to enhance clarity and effectiveness in the tests.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_WUb9HRYEap69falR2QV3Qm1X|fc_0f9d00fa7ef477820169f70977881881969577c2ecae11d14e\", \"name\": \"write\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/io.quarkus.gizmo/gizmo2/2.0.0.Beta10/src/test/java/io_quarkus_gizmo/gizmo2/AnnotationCreatorTest.java\", \"content\": \"/*\\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\\n *\\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\\n */\\npackage io_quarkus_gizmo.gizmo2;\\n\\nimport static org.assert